<dl id="n08079g"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n08" href="#n08079g">N08 (VI.B.6)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n08all.htm#n08079g"> 79(g)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> cuistha = 12th <font color="red"><sup><teeny>|a</teeny></sup></font>famine<font color="red"><sup><teeny>a|</teeny></sup></font> word meaning the / hunger voluntarily endured / by a person who will / not eat <font color="red"><sup><teeny>|a</teeny></sup></font>his favourite<font color="red"><sup><teeny>a|</teeny></sup></font> food prepared / for him because the person / who prepared it = ? <small>Blue</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n08079g"><li>FW 422.18 </li><li><a href="../../flex/pD/lexpD.htm#n08079g">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/pD/l39pD.htm#n08079g">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n08079g">MS NLI 15/9B-11</ms> </li><li>JJA not reproduced <a name="pAd11" href="../../FF/fdra/pda.htm#pDd11">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/pD/pDd11.htm#n08079g">Draft: III&sect;1D.11</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">A language has always many terms for those things that interest the speakers in their daily doings; &hellip; And when we read that the Araucanians (in Chile) distinguished nicely in their languages between a great many shades of hunger, our compassion is excited, as Gabelentz remarks. <font color="green">[n2: Gabelentz, <i>Sprachwissenschaft</i> 1891, 463.]</font> <small> Otto Jespersen, <a name="OJGS" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#OJGS"><cite title="source">The Growth and Structure of the English Language</cite></a>, 4th ed. (Jul 1923) 52</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
